gory:Xbox One]]\n[[Category:Subscription services]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox online service\n| name = EA Access\n| logo = EA Access 2016.png\n| logo caption = EA Access logo since 2016\n| developer = [[Electronic Arts]]\n| key_people = \n| launched = {{Start date|2014|08|11}} (Xbox One)<br>{{Start date|2019|07|24}} (PlayStation 4)\n| platform = [[Xbox One]]<br>[[PlayStation 4]]<br>[[Steam (service)|Steam]]\n| pricing = {{USD}}4.99 per month<br>{{USD}}29.99 per year\n| website = {{Official website|https://www.ea.com/ea-access}}\n| status = Active\n| type = Subscription gaming service\n}}\n\n'''EA Access''' is a [[subscription service|subscription-based]] [[video game]] service from [[Electronic Arts]] for the [[Microsoft]] [[Xbox One]] and [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 4]] platforms, offering access to selected games published by Electronic Arts along with additional incentives. A similar service, [[Origin (digital distribution software)#Origin Access|Origin Access]], is available for [[Microsoft Windows]] PCs.<ref name=\"Origin Access\">{{cite web|url=https://www.origin.com/gbr/en-us/store/origin-access|title=Origin Access|website=Origin|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEA Access was pitched to both Microsoft for the Xbox One and Sony for the PlayStation 4, although Sony initially declined to participate as they did not believe it provided value to their customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.trustedreviews.com/news/ea-access-sony-ps4-finally-gets-release-date-3888742|title=EA Access for Sony PS4 finally gets its release date|last=Smith|first=Chris|date=June 28, 2019|work=Trusted Reviews|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> EA Access launched first on Xbox One on August 11, 2014, and later arrived to the PlayStation 4 on July 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ram\u00e9e |first=Jordan |date=May 7, 2019 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-access-coming-to-ps4-this-july/1100-6466686/ |title=EA Access Coming To PS4 This July |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:EA Access 2014.png|alt=|thumb|200x200px|EA Access logo, 2014\u20132016]]\nEA Access membership can be purchased in one-month or 12-month increments, either from the Xbox Games Store or from selected third-party retailers.<ref name=\"Engadget\">{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/07/29/ea-access-subscription-gaming-xbox-one/ | title='EA Access' subscription on Xbox One brings all-you-can-eat gaming for $5 per month | publisher=AOL | work=Engadget | date=July 29, 2014 | accessdate=July 30, 2014 | author=Lawler, Richard | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730212848/http://www.engadget.com/2014/07/29/ea-access-subscription-gaming-xbox-one/ | archivedate=July 30, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref> Members have unlimited access to the full versions of a selection of games published by EA, dubbed \"the Vault\", for as long as their membership is active.<ref name=\"Engadget\"/>  If membership is suspended, the games can no longer be played, but all progress and game saves are retained.  Members may also purchase games available from EA Access outright, along with other EA games and [[Downloadable content|DLC]], at a discounted price.<ref name=\"Engadget\"/>  EA Access does not require users to have a paid [[Xbox Live]] membership, although a Gold-level membership is required for use of any multiplayer features that are included in Access-enabled games.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/07/29/ea-unveils-xbox-one-subscription-service-ea-access/ | title=EA unveils Xbox One subscription service, EA Access | publisher=AOL | work=Joystiq | date=July 30, 2014 | accessdate=July 30, 2014 | author=Cavalli, Earnest | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730212850/http://www.joystiq.com/2014/07/29/ea-unveils-xbox-one-subscription-service-ea-access/ | archivedate=July 30, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGames are added to the Vault at EA's discretion, such as making a title available on Access a set number of days after its retail launch.<ref name=\"GS-Vault\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-promises-not-to-remove-games-from-ea-access-fre/1100-6421567/ | title=EA Promises Not to Remove Games From EA Access' Free Games Vault | publisher=CBS Interactive | work=GameSpot | date=August 7, 2014 | accessdate=August 7, 2014 | author=Pereira, Chris | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140807222634/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-promises-not-to-remove-games-from-ea-access-fre/1100-6421567/ | archivedate=August 7, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref>  Although the Terms of Service allow EA to remove titles with 30 days' notice,<ref name=\"GS-Vault\"/> EA has pledged that games will not be removed at a later date.<ref name=\"GS-Vault\"/>  However, EA announced on July 20, 2017 that ''[[FIFA 14]]'' would be removed from the Vault on October 18, 2017 due to the decision to end online support for the title.<ref name=\"FIFA 14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/ea-access/news/fifa-14-will-leave-ea-access-on-october-18|title=FIFA 14 will leave EA Access on October 18|work=ea.com|publisher=Electronic Arts|date=July 20, 2017|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> The game will remain playable in offline mode for users who installed it prior to its removal date, but if the game is removed from the console after that date, it cannot be reinstalled.<ref name=\"GS-FIFA 14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-access-vault-removing-a-game-for-the-first-time/1100-6452149/|title=EA Access Vault Removing A Game For The First Time [UPDATE]|author=Chris Pereira|work=gamespot.com|publisher=CBS Interactive, Inc.|date=August 2, 2017|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> EA described the removal of FIFA 14 as a \"unique circumstance specific to the title\" that was not representative of their future plans for EA Access.<ref name=\"GS-FIFA 14\"/> On April 26, 2018, it was announced that ''[[Rory McIlroy PGA Tour]]'' would also be removed from the Vault on May 22, 2018 due to the game being delisted from the Xbox Store on that date.<ref>https://www.ea.com/ea-access/news/rory-mcilroy-pga-tour-will-leave-ea-access-on-may-22</ref>\n\nUsers who pre-order upcoming games through Access are able download special limited versions of the games, released five days prior to the retail launch. EA described these early-release versions as not being more traditional [[game demo|demos]], but instead full-featured but time-limited versions, with the exact extent of content varying from game to game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/07/new-details-emerge-on-ea-access-game-selection-and-trials | title=New Details Emerge on EA Access' Game Selection and Trials | publisher=Ziff Davis | work=IGN | date=August 7, 2014 | accessdate=August 7, 2014 | author=Sirani, Jordan | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140807222635/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/07/new-details-emerge-on-ea-access-game-selection-and-trials | archivedate=August 7, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref>  Any progress earned within these limited versions will carry over to the full retail version.<ref name=\"Engadget\"/>\n\nGames published on the EA Partners and/or EA Originals labels are not eligible for EA Access benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/07/29/ea-unveils-xbox-one-subscription-service-ea-access/|title=EA unveils Xbox One subscription service, EA Access [update]|author=Earnest Cavalli|work=[[Joystiq]]|date=August 10, 2014|accessdate=December 10, 2014}}</ref> However, ''[[Titanfall]]'' was added to the Vault in June 2015, as part of an [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2015|E3 2015]] promotion that also enabled a free trial for all Xbox One owners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2015/06/15/titanfall-and-dragon-age-inquisition-joining-ea-access-vault-vault-opening-to-all-gold-members-this-week.aspx|title=Titanfall And Dragon Age Inquisition Joining EA Access Vault, Vault Opening To All Gold Members This Week|author=Kyle Hilliard|work=gameinformer.com|publisher=GameStop|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Titanfall 2]]'' was also added to the vault in July 2017.\n\nEA Access subscribers are able to receive [[downloadable content]] for games in the Vault free at during various limited time periods, such as the Naval Strike and Second Assault DLCs for ''[[Battlefield 4]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Saed |first=Sherif |url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/08/28/battlefield-4-dlc-naval-strike-free-this-week-for-ea-access-members/ |title=Battlefield 4 DLC Naval Strike free this week for EA Access members |publisher=VG247 |date=2015-08-28 |accessdate=2016-04-11}}</ref> Subscribers who download the free DLCs offered during the free period are able to keep them regardless of subscription status. On May 3, 2016, Premium access for ''Battlefield 4'' and ''[[Battlefield Hardline]]'' were offered free for a limited period of time, enabling subscribers to download all released expansions for both games at no cost.<ref>https://www.ea.com/ea-access/landing-page/battlefield-4</ref> While ''Battlefield 4'' Premium content can only be accessed with an active subscription, subscribers were allowed to keep ''Hardline'' Premium features regardless of subscription status. The season pass for ''[[Star Wars Battlefront (2015 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront]]'' was made available at no cost for subscribers on July 7, 2017.<ref>https://www.ea.com/ea-access/news/swbf-dlc-in-the-vault</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2016, EA Access expanded to include [[Xbox 360]] titles via the Xbox One's backward compatibility feature, starting with the original ''[[Plants vs. Zombies]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Saed |first=Sherif |url=http://www.vg247.com/2016/03/01/ea-access-plants-vs-zombies-xbox-360-backwards-compatible/ |title=EA Access adds first non-Xbox One game to the vault |publisher=VG247 |date=2016-03-01 |accessdate=2016-04-11}}</ref> ''[[Dead Space (2008 video game)|Dead Space]]'' was added (without any official announcement) on March 31.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williatham |first=Atle |url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/ea-access-adds-backwards-compatible-dead-space-to-xbox-one-3435475 |title=EA Access adds Backwards Compatible Dead Space to Xbox One |website=Gamezone.com |date=2016-04-01 |accessdate=2016-04-11}}</ref> On January 17, 2018, ''[[Black (video game)|Black]]'', released for [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] in 2006, was added to the Vault.\n\nEA announced that alongside bringing its catalog back to [[Steam (service)|Steam]] in October 2019, that it would also release a version of EA Access for Steam users with a library comparable to the Xbox and PlayStation versions.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/29/20937055/ea-games-steam-access-subscription-service-pc-storefront-jedi-fallen-order-sales | title = EA games are returning to Steam along with the EA Access subscription service | first=  Chaim  | last = Gartenburg | date = October 29, 2019 | accessdate = October 29, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\nEA Access debuted in beta form exclusively on Xbox One on July 29, 2014,<ref name=\"Engadget\"/> and was officially launched on August 11, 2014.<ref name=\"GS-Launch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-access-now-available-on-xbox-one/1100-6421641/|title=EA Access Now Available On Xbox One|author=Eddie Makuch|work=gamespot.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|date=August 11, 2014|accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref> Electronic Arts approached both Sony and Microsoft with the service, but Sony declined to make it available on their [[PlayStation 4]] console.<ref name=\"IGN-Sony\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/07/30/sony-passed-on-ea-access-for-ps4-as-its-not-good-value | title=Sony Passed on EA Access for PS4 as It's Not 'Good Value' | publisher=Ziff Davis | work=IGN | date=July 30, 2014 | accessdate=July 30, 2014 | author=Karmali, Luke | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730212851/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/07/30/sony-passed-on-ea-access-for-ps4-as-its-not-good-value | archivedate=July 30, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref> A similar version called ''[[Origin (digital distribution software)|Origin]] Access'' launched on January 12, 2016 on PC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.origin.com/en-us/store/origin-access |title=PC Game Subscription &#124; Origin Access &#124; Origin Games |website=Origin.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-11}}</ref>\n\nShares of video game retailer [[GameStop]], which sells both new and used games, fell over five percent after Electronic Arts' announcement.<ref name=\"GameStopStock\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-shares-tumble-after-ea-access-announcemen/1100-6421382/ | title=GameStop Shares Tumble After EA Access Announcement | publisher=CBS Interactive | work=GameSpot | date=July 29, 2014 | accessdate=July 30, 2014 | author=Makuch, Eddie | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730212852/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-shares-tumble-after-ea-access-announcemen/1100-6421382/ | archivedate=July 30, 2014 | url-status=live}}</ref> A similar price drop occurred after PlayStation Now was first announced and that the stock price subsequently recovered.<ref name=\"GameStopStock\"/> GameStop will be one of the retailers selling EA Access memberships.<ref name=\"GameStopStock\"/>\n\n==Games in the Vault==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Developer !! Xbox One !! PlayStation 4 !! Notes/References\n|-\n| ''[[Alice: Madness Returns]]'' || [[Spicy Horse]] || {{Ya}} || {{Na}} || <ref>{{cite tweet |user=EAAccess |author=EA Access |date=May 22, 2019 |number=1131326391142703104 |title=Can Alice save Wonderland, and herself? You decide |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Anthem (video game)|Anthem]]'' || [[BioWare]] || {{Ya}} || {{Ya}} || <ref>{{cite web |last=S. Good |first=Owen |date=September 12, 2019 |url=https://www.polygon.com