 at 2008 Betty Mitchell Awards |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/487721518/ |accessdate=August 25, 2019 |work=Calgary Herald |date=August 26, 2008}}</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/the-drowning-girls-surfaces-with-4-calgary-theatre-awards-1.763735 \"The Drowning Girls surfaces with 4 Calgary theatre awards\"]. ''CBC Arts'', Aug 26, 2008</ref>\n|-\n| 12th || Max Bell Theatre, [[EPCOR CENTRE for the Performing Arts]] || August 24, 2009 ||\n|-\n| 13th || Max Bell Theatre, [[EPCOR CENTRE for the Performing Arts]] || August 30, 2010 || AJ Demers <br/> Julie Orton\n|-\n\n| 14th || Stage West || August 20, 2011 || Karen Johnson-Diamond <br/> Kevin Rothery\n|-\n| 15th || Stage West || August 27, 2012 || Russell Bowers\n|-\n| 16th || Stage West || August 26, 2013 || Nicole Zylstra <br/> Stafford Perry\n|-\n| 17th || Stage West || August 18, 2014 || Stephen Hair<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brooks |first1=Bill |title=Betty Mitchell Awards honour the best of city's theatre world |url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/entertainment/Betty+Mitchell+Awards+honour+best+city+theatre+world/10177957/story.html |accessdate=August 25, 2019 |work=Calgary Herald |date=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 18th || Vertigo Theatre || August 24, 2015 || Julie Orton\n|-\n| 19th || Vertigo Theatre || 2016 || Josh Bertwistle, Carly McKee <br/> Chris Enright, Nicole Zylstra\n|-\n| 20th || Vertigo Theatre || 2017 || Mark Bellamy <br/> Selena Wong\n|-\n| 21st || Vertigo Theatre || June 25, 2018 || Katherine Fadum<br/>Michael Tan<ref>{{cite news |last1=Theatre Alberta Staff |title=Interview with Braden Griffiths: 21st Annual Betty Mitchell Awards |url=https://www.theatrealberta.com/2018/06/20/news-calgary-interview-with-braden-griffiths-21st-annual-betty-mitchell-awards/ |accessdate=August 25, 2019 |work=Theatre Alberta |date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 22nd || Vertigo Theatre || June 24, 2019 || Raven Virginia\n|-\n|}\n\n==Statue update==\nThe original Betty Mitchell Award statue, designed by local Calgary sculptor, Petronella Overes, was inspired by the geography surrounding Calgary.  It was a steel base containing a glass monolith with motifs of mountains and prairies.  In 2007 for the 10th anniversary of the awards she redesigned it replacing the steel base with powder coated aluminum and increased the contrast in the tone and texture of the awards metal and glass.<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Clark\n | first = B\n | title = Award gets an update\n | newspaper = [[Calgary Herald]]\n | pages = C2\n | date = 27 August 2014\n | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/487996800\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date = 15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Award received its most recent design update in 2014 when the Overes design was replaced with a multi-color teardrop-shaped glass sculpture created by a local glass blowing collective, Bee Kingdom Glass. Being hand blown each one is unique.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Black Theatre Workshop]]\n* [[Dora Mavor Moore Award]]\n* [[Elizabeth Sterling Haynes Award]]\n* [[Floyd S. Chalmers Canadian Play Award]]\n* [[Gascon-Thomas Award]]\n* [[Jessie Richardson Theatre Award]]\n* [[Rideau Awards]]\n* [[Robert Merritt Awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Betty Mitchell Awards [http://www.bettymitchellawards.com Official Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Betty Award}}\n[[Category:Theatre stubs]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Canadian theatre awards]]\n[[Category:Culture of Calgary]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toBetty Mitchell(link changed toBetty Mitchell (theatre director)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Award"}
{"title_page": "Maryam Rajavi", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian leftist politician, leader of the People's Mujahedin of Iran}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Maryam Rajavi\n| image = Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu.png\n| caption = Rajavi's image in 1980 election posters\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran]], [[Imperial State of Iran|Iran]]\n| birth_name  = Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu\n| spouse = {{plainlist|\n*{{marriage |[[Mehdi Abrishamchi]]|1980|1985|end=div}}<ref name=\"TNY\">{{cite journal|journal=The New Yorker|volume=82|issue=1\u201311|pp=54\u201355|publisher=F-R Publishing Corporation|year=2006|title=Exiles: How Iran's expatriates are gaming the nuclear threat|author=Connie Bruck|quote=This transition was epitomized by Rajavi's involvement, in 1985, with Maryam Azodanlu. Maryam was already married, to Mehdi Abrishamchi, one of Rajavi's close associates. Rajavi overcame that fact by making the romance a matter of revolutionary necessity. First, he said that he was making Maryam his co-leader-and that it would transform thinking about the role of women throughout the Muslim world. Then, about a month later, it was announced that Maryam was divorced from Abrishamchi and that the two co-leaders would marry, in order to further the \"ideological revolution.\"}}</ref>\n*{{marriage |[[Massoud Rajavi]]|1985}}<ref name=\"TNY\"/>\n}}\n| children = 1 daughter<ref>{{citation|first=Georgie Anne|last=Geyer|title=Iranian Exiles Have A Committed Leader In Maryam Rajavi|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1994-08-26-9408260149-story.html|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=26 August 1996|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n| organization = [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n| module3             = \n  {{Collapsed infobox section begin|MEK positions|expanded=yes|cont=yes|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}{{Infobox officeholder\n   |embed = yes\n   | office1        = President-elect of the [[National Council of Resistance]]\n   | term_start1    = 22 October 1993<ref name=\"President\u2013elect\">{{cite book|chapter=Iran: The People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran|title=Iran: Outlaw, Outcast, Or Normal Country?|p=97|publisher=Nova Publishers|year=2001|author1=Kenneth Katzman|editor=Albert V. Benliot|isbn=1560729546}}</ref>\n   | term_end1      = \n   | predecessor1  = [[Abolhassan Banisadr]]{{efn|Banisadr who was affiliated with the [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]] from 1981 to 1984, was considered as the \"President of Iran\" in the claimed government by the council.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ensani.ir/fa/content/49872/default.aspx |title=\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u0644\u06cc \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0648\u0645\u062a\u060c \u0628\u0646\u06cc\u200c\u0635\u062f\u0631 \u0648 \u0631\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u060c \u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0626\u062a\u0644\u0627\u0641 \u062a\u0627 \u062c\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u06cc |date=July 2008 |origyear=Tir 1387 |author=Kian Parsa |language=Persian |number=52 |journal=Shahrvand Magazine |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003021728/http://ensani.ir/fa/content/49872/default.aspx |archivedate=3 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The office was vacant after Banisadr.}}\n   | office2        = Co\u2013equal Leader of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n   | term_start2    = 27 January 1985<ref name=\"Co-equal Leader\">{{cite book|title=Iran's Revolutionary Guard: The Threat That Grows While America Sleeps|p=208|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc|year=2012|author1=Steven O'Hern|isbn=1597977012}}</ref>\n   | term_end2      = \n   | predecessor2   = [[Massoud Rajavi]] {{small|(as leader)}}\n   | alongside2     = [[Massoud Rajavi]] (until 2003){{efn|Since 2003 [[Massoud Rajavi]] has disappeared and leadership of the group has practically passed to his wife Maryam Rajavi.<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Terrorism|p=454|series=Historical Dictionaries of War, Revolution, and Civil Unrest|edition=3|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|author1=Stephen Sloan|author2=Sean K. Anderson|isbn=0810863111}}</ref>}}\n   | office3        = Secretay-General of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n   | term_start3    = 8 October 1989\n   | term_end3      = 22 October 1993\n   | predecessor3   = [[Massoud Rajavi]]\n   | successor3     = Fahimeh Arvani\n   | office4        = Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the National Liberation Army\n   | term_start4    = 20 June 1987\n   | term_end4      = 22 October 1993\n   | successor4     =\n}}\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Maryam Rajavi''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645 \u0631\u062c\u0648\u06cc}}, {{Nee|Qajar-Azodanlu}}, {{lang-fa|\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645 \u0642\u062c\u0631 \u0639\u0636\u062f\u0627\u0646\u0644\u0648}}) is the leader of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] (MEK), an organization trying to overthrow the [[Iranian government]], and President-elect of its [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]] (NCRI). She is the wife of [[Massoud Rajavi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Maryam Rajavi|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2980279.stm|website=BBC News|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRajavi was born Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu on 4 December 1953 in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]].<ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{citation|first=Elizabeth|last=Sleeman|title=The International Who's Who of Women 2002|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2001|isbn=9781857431223|page=464|entry=RAJAVI, Maryam}}</ref> She was in a middle-class civil servant family descended from a member of the [[Qajar dynasty]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Craig S.|title=Exiled Iranians Try to Foment Revolution From France|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/24/international/europe/24rajavi.html?_r=0|accessdate=7 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 September 2005}}</ref> She attended the [[Sharif University of Technology]] in Iran, earning a B.S. in [[metallurgy]].<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n==Political career==\nRajavi has stated that her political activism started when she was twenty-two after her sister Narges was killed by [[SAVAK]].<ref name=nytimes/> Then she became a member of the [[People's Mojahedin of Iran]] (PMOI/MEK), and began her political career. Maryam Rajavi served as deputy commander and MEK Secretary General until 1993. On 22 October 1993, the [[National Council of Resistance of Iran|NCRI]] elected Maryam to be \"Iran\u2019s interim President\" if the NCRI were to assume power in Iran.<ref>{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Kenneth |last=Katzman |chapter=Iran: The People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran |title = Iran: Outlaw, Outcast, Or Normal Country? |publisher = [[Nova]] |year=2001 |editor-first = Albert V. |editor-last = Benliot |page=97-98 | isbn = 978-1-56072-954-9 }}</ref>\n\nRajavi served as an organizer of the anti-Shah student movement in the 1970s. In 1979, she became an official of the social section of the PMOI/MEK, where she served until 1981. Rajavi was a parliamentary candidate in 1980.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/> \n\nIn 1982, Rajavi was transferred to [[Auvers-sur-Oise]], [[\u00cele-de-France]] where the political headquarters of the Mojahedin was located.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n\nIn 1985, she became Joint-Leader of the PMOI and served as the Secretary General between 1989 and 1993.<ref>{{citation|first=Ronen|last=Cohen|title=The Rise and Fall of the Mojahedin Khalq, 1987\u20131997: Their Survival After the Islamic Revolution and Resistance to the Islamic Republic of Iran|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84519-270-9|page=12}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement that condemned the [[ISIS]] attacks [[2017 Tehran attacks|against Iran's parliament and the tomb]] of the Islamic Republic's founder, Rajavi stated: \"ISIS's conduct clearly benefits the Iranian regime's Supreme Leader Khamenei, who wholeheartedly welcomes it as an opportunity to overcome his regime's regional and international impasse and isolation. The founder and the number one [[Iran and state-sponsored terrorism|state sponsor of terror]] is thus trying to switch the place of murderer and the victim and portray the central banker of terrorism as a victim.\"<ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/just-because-isis-attacked-iran-doesnt-mean-iran-isnt-supporting-terrorism/article/2625674 Just because ISIS attacked Iran doesn't mean Iran isn't supporting terrorism]. 12 June 2017. Retrieved 13 June 2017</ref>\n\nA 10-point manifesto published by Maryam Rajavi sets out a programme to transform Iran. She states her commitment to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and to other international instruments. She calls for the abolition of the death penalty, the creation of a modern legal system and the independence of judges. Rajavi would end Tehran\u2019s funding of [[Hamas]], [[Hezbollah]] and other militant groups and is committed to peaceful coexistence, relations with all countries and respect for the United Nations charter.<ref>[http://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2016-12-08/debates/1117FCF0-EE8C-4A7A-BED2-DE9108AD65DC/IranHumanRights?highlight=Maryam%20Rajavi#contribution-6C120466-1CAA-4B8A-9EB6-E39D862B33EB Iran: Human Rights Debate in the UK House of Lords, House of Lord Hansard, 8 December 2016 ] [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This article contains quotations from this source, which is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/  Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref>  The manifesto also contains the statement that 'We recognize private property, private investment and the market economy.'<ref>https://www.usfliberty.org/maryam-rajavi/</ref>.\n\nRajavi presented her plan at the Council of Europe in 2006, which supports complete gender equality in political and social rights and, specifically, a commitment to equal participation of women in political leadership. Her 10-point plan for the future of Iran stipulates that any form of discrimination against women would be abolished and that women would enjoy the right to choose their clothing freely. It also includes the ending of cruel and degrading punishments.<ref>[http://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-06-28/debates/92B47430-75B2-40B5-9FA6-76A24E8D1E7C/HumanRightsInIran?highlight=Maryam%20Rajavi#contribution-85B1A801-C8A8-449C-8097-8267042F9C10 Human Rights in Iran, Debate in the UK House of Commons, House of Commons Hansard, 28 June 2016] [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This article contains quotations from this source, which is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/  Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref>\n\nOn October 2011 [[Theresa May]] banned Maryam Rajavi from coming to Britain in a trip where she was to \"explain how women are mistreated in Iran\". The high court then sued Theresa May, with Lord Carlile of Berriew (the Government's former independent reviewer of counter-terrorism laws) saying that May's decision \"could be viewed as appeasing the Mullahs\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/may-appeases-iran-with-ban-on-opposition-leader-bmdfx3w70fg |title=Iraqi court seeks arrest of Iranian exiles|access-date=21 January 2020|publisher=[[The Times]]|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/may-is-appeasing-iran-by-blocking-dissidents-visit-7445975.html |title=May 'is appeasing Iran' by blocking dissident's visit|access-date=21 January 2020|publisher=The Standard|}}</ref> In 2014, [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] dismissed an appeal from Lord Carlile of Berriew QC and others and upheld it to maintain the ban, which had originally being implemented in 1997. Members of the UK House of Lords argued that the Home Secretary was \"violating Article 10 (freedom of expression) of the European Convention of Human Rights (the Convention)\", saying that \"Home Secretary\u2019s reasons were legally irrelevant, because they depended on the potential reaction of a foreign state which did not share the values embodied in the Convention.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barakatt|first1=Marina|title=U.K. Supreme Court Upholds Home Secretary\u2019s Decision to Prevent an Iranian Politician from Entering the U.K. (November 12, 2014)|url=https://www.asil.org/blogs/uk-supreme-court-upholds-home-secretary%E2%80%99s-decision-prevent-iranian-politician-entering-uk|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=14 September 2016|publisher=The American Society of International Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=R (on the application of Lord Carlile of Berriew QC and others) (Appellants) v Secretary of State for the Home Department (Respondent) [2014] UKSC 60|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927010314/https://www.supremecourt.uk/decided-cases/docs/UKSC_2013_0098_PressSummary.pdf|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/decided-cases/docs/UKSC_2013_0098_PressSummary.pdf|archive-date=25 November 2017|accessdate=14 September 2016|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom}}</ref> Rajavi is not excluded from any other European country and engages regularly with parliamentarians in the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parliamentarians lose Maryam Rajavi court battle|url=http://www.hillingdontimes.co.uk/news/11596593.Parliamentarians_lose_Maryam_Rajavi_court_battle/?ref=mr|website=Hillingdon & Uxbridge Times|publisher=Hillingdon & Uxbridge Times|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Election (Constituency) !! Votes !! % !! Rank !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n|1980||[[1980 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]] {{small|([[Tehran, Rey, Shemiranat and Eslamshahr (electoral district)|Tehran, Rey and Shemiranat]])}}||221,831||10.4||67th\n| style=\"background-color:#C66\"|Lost\n|<ref>{{citation|date=5 April 1980|orig-year=16 Farvardin 1359|access-date=20 January 2020|title=\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0632\u062f\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0647 \u0628\u06cc\u0634 \u0627\u0632 \u06f1\u06f0 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0631\u0623\u06cc \u0622\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0647\u200c\u0627\u0646\u062f|url=https://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/detail/Manchester~18~18~906~226953:15m4471|newspaper=Kayhan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429044711/https://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/detail/Manchester~18~18~906~226953:15m4471|archive-date=29 April 2019|number=10964|page=3|language=Persian|trans-title=Names of Tehran candidates who gained more than 10,000 votes|via=The University of Manchester Library|id=15m4471|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Trials ==\n=== France ===\nOn 17 June 2003, Maryam Rajavi was arrested by [[Paris Police Prefecture]] alongside some 150 MEK members.<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/2996132.stm|title=Paris police target Iranian groups|date=17 June 2003|access-date=28 December 2016|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Rajavi released on bail|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=4 July 2003|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/07/200849135442456351.html}}</ref> Rajavi denied the charges, saying \"the case was mounted to appease Iran.\"<ref>{{citation|first= |last= |title=France drops charges against Iran opposition group |publisher=Fox News|date= |access-date=|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/france-drops-charges-against-iran-opposition-group}}</ref> All charges were later dropped.<ref name=\"reuters\"/><ref>{{citation|first=David|last=Jolly|title=France Will Drop Charges Against Iranian Dissidents |publisher=The New York Times|date=12 May 2011|access-date=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/world/europe/13iht-iran13.html}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters\">{{citation|title=France drops case against Iranian dissidents after 11-year probe |publisher=Reuters|date=17 September 2014|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-iran-ncri/france-drops-case-against-iranian-dissidents-after-11-year-probe-idUSKBN0HC1OR20140917}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=France Drops Case Against Iranian Dissidents|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=17 September 2014|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/france-drops-iran-dissidents-case/26590826.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq ===\nIn July 2010, the [[Supreme Iraqi Criminal Tribunal|Iraqi High Tribunal]] issued an [[arrest warrant]] for 39 MEK members, including Rajavi, \"due to evidence that confirms they committed [[crimes against humanity]]\" by \"involvement with the [[Iraqi Intelligence Service|former Iraqi security forces]] in suppressing the [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|1991 uprising]] against the former Iraqi regime and the killing of Iraqi citizens\". The MEK have denied the charges, saying that they constitute a \"politically motivated decision and it\u2019s the last gift presented from the government of Nuri al-Maliki to the Iranian government\".<ref name=\"cah\">{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|editor=Rania El Gamal; David Stamp|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE66A0A0|title=Iraqi court seeks arrest of Iranian exiles|date=11 July 2010|access-date=28 December 2016|publisher=[[Reuters]]|quote=Rajavi\u2019s wife Maryam, leader of the French-based National Council of Resistance of Iran (NCRI), the PMOI\u2019s political wing, was also included in the warrant, Abdul Sahib added.}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Iran|Biography}}\n*[[List of Iranian women]]\n*[[List of people from Tehran]] \n*[[France\u2013Iran relations]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.maryam-rajavi.com/en/ }}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Massoud Rajavi]]|as=Leader of People's Mujahedin of Iran}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Co-leader of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]|years=1985\u2013present|alongside=[[Massoud Rajavi]]}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Abolhassan Banisadr]]|as=President of Iran in pretence}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President-elect of the [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Massoud Rajavi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretay-General of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]|years=1989\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=Fahimeh Arvani}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] military wing|years=1987\u20131993}}\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajavi, Maryam}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sharif University of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Mujahedin of Iran politicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian women in politics]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by Iraq]]\n[[Category:National Council of Resistance of Iran members]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on crimes against humanity charges]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian leftist politician, leader of the People's Mujahedin of Iran}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Maryam Rajavi\n| image = Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu.png\n| caption = Rajavi's image in 1980 election posters\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran]], [[Imperial State of Iran|Iran]]\n| birth_name  = Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu\n| spouse = {{plainlist|\n*{{marriage |[[Mehdi Abrishamchi]]|1980|1985|end=div}}<ref name=\"TNY\">{{cite journal|journal=The New Yorker|volume=82|issue=1\u201311|pp=54\u201355|publisher=F-R Publishing Corporation|year=2006|title=Exiles: How Iran's expatriates are gaming the nuclear threat|author=Connie Bruck|quote=This transition was epitomized by Rajavi's involvement, in 1985, with Maryam Azodanlu. Maryam was already married, to Mehdi Abrishamchi, one of Rajavi's close associates. Rajavi overcame that fact by making the romance a matter of revolutionary necessity. First, he said that he was making Maryam his co-leader-and that it would transform thinking about the role of women throughout the Muslim world. Then, about a month later, it was announced that Maryam was divorced from Abrishamchi and that the two co-leaders would marry, in order to further the \"ideological revolution.\"}}</ref>\n*{{marriage |[[Massoud Rajavi]]|1985}}<ref name=\"TNY\"/>\n}}\n| children = 1 daughter<ref>{{citation|first=Georgie Anne|last=Geyer|title=Iranian Exiles Have A Committed Leader In Maryam Rajavi|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1994-08-26-9408260149-story.html|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=26 August 1996|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n| organization = [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n| module3             = \n  {{Collapsed infobox section begin|MEK positions|expanded=yes|cont=yes|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}{{Infobox officeholder\n   |embed = yes\n   | office1        = President-elect of the [[National Council of Resistance]]\n   | term_start1    = 22 October 1993<ref name=\"President\u2013elect\">{{cite book|chapter=Iran: The People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran|title=Iran: Outlaw, Outcast, Or Normal Country?|p=97|publisher=Nova Publishers|year=2001|author1=Kenneth Katzman|editor=Albert V. Benliot|isbn=1560729546}}</ref>\n   | term_end1      = \n   | predecessor1  = [[Abolhassan Banisadr]]{{efn|Banisadr who was affiliated with the [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]] from 1981 to 1984, was considered as the \"President of Iran\" in the claimed government by the council.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ensani.ir/fa/content/49872/default.aspx |title=\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u0644\u06cc \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0648\u0645\u062a\u060c \u0628\u0646\u06cc\u200c\u0635\u062f\u0631 \u0648 \u0631\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u060c \u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0626\u062a\u0644\u0627\u0641 \u062a\u0627 \u062c\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u06cc |date=July 2008 |origyear=Tir 1387 |author=Kian Parsa |language=Persian |number=52 |journal=Shahrvand Magazine |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003021728/http://ensani.ir/fa/content/49872/default.aspx |archivedate=3 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The office was vacant after Banisadr.}}\n   | office2        = Co\u2013equal Leader of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n   | term_start2    = 27 January 1985<ref name=\"Co-equal Leader\">{{cite book|title=Iran's Revolutionary Guard: The Threat That Grows While America Sleeps|p=208|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc|year=2012|author1=Steven O'Hern|isbn=1597977012}}</ref>\n   | term_end2      = \n   | predecessor2   = [[Massoud Rajavi]] {{small|(as leader)}}\n   | alongside2     = [[Massoud Rajavi]] (until 2003){{efn|Since 2003 [[Massoud Rajavi]] has disappeared and leadership of the group has practically passed to his wife Maryam Rajavi.<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Terrorism|p=454|series=Historical Dictionaries of War, Revolution, and Civil Unrest|edition=3|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|author1=Stephen Sloan|author2=Sean K. Anderson|isbn=0810863111}}</ref>}}\n   | office3        = Secretay-General of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]\n   | term_start3    = 8 October 1989\n   | term_end3      = 22 October 1993\n   | predecessor3   = [[Massoud Rajavi]]\n   | successor3     = Fahimeh Arvani\n   | office4        = Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the National Liberation Army\n   | term_start4    = 20 June 1987\n   | term_end4      = 22 October 1993\n   | successor4     =\n}}\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Maryam Rajavi''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645 \u0631\u062c\u0648\u06cc}}, {{Nee|Qajar-Azodanlu}}, {{lang-fa|\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645 \u0642\u062c\u0631 \u0639\u0636\u062f\u0627\u0646\u0644\u0648}}) is the leader of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] (MEK), an organization trying to overthrow the [[Iranian government]], and President-elect of its [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]] (NCRI). She is the wife of [[Massoud Rajavi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Maryam Rajavi|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2980279.stm|website=BBC News|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRajavi was born Maryam Qajar-Azodanlu on 4 December 1953 in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]].<ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{citation|first=Elizabeth|last=Sleeman|title=The International Who's Who of Women 2002|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2001|isbn=9781857431223|page=464|entry=RAJAVI, Maryam}}</ref> She was in a middle-class civil servant family descended from a member of the [[Qajar dynasty]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Craig S.|title=Exiled Iranians Try to Foment Revolution From France|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/24/international/europe/24rajavi.html?_r=0|accessdate=7 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 September 2005}}</ref> She attended the [[Sharif University of Technology]] in Iran, earning a B.S. in [[metallurgy]].<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n==Political career==\nRajavi has stated that her political activism started when she was twenty-two after her sister Narges was killed by [[SAVAK]].<ref name=nytimes/> Then she became a member of the [[People's Mojahedin of Iran]] (PMOI/MEK), and began her political career. Maryam Rajavi served as deputy commander and MEK Secretary General until 1993. On 22 October 1993, the [[NCRI]] elected Maryam to be \"Iran\u2019s interim President\" if the NCRI were to assume power in Iran.<ref>{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Kenneth |last=Katzman |chapter=Iran: The People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran |title = Iran: Outlaw, Outcast, Or Normal Country? |publisher = [[Nova]] |year=2001 |editor-first = Albert V. |editor-last = Benliot |page=97-98 | isbn = 978-1-56072-954-9 }}</ref>\n\nRajavi served as an organizer of the anti-Shah student movement in the 1970s. In 1979, she became an official of the social section of the PMOI/MEK, where she served until 1981. Rajavi was a parliamentary candidate in 1980.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/> \n\nIn 1982, Rajavi was transferred to [[Auvers-sur-Oise]], [[\u00cele-de-France]] where the political headquarters of the Mojahedin was located.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n\nIn 1985, she became Joint-Leader of the PMOI and served as the Secretary General between 1989 and 1993.<ref>{{citation|first=Ronen|last=Cohen|title=The Rise and Fall of the Mojahedin Khalq, 1987\u20131997: Their Survival After the Islamic Revolution and Resistance to the Islamic Republic of Iran|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84519-270-9|page=12}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement that condemned the [[ISIS]] attacks [[2017 Tehran attacks|against Iran's parliament and the tomb]] of the Islamic Republic's founder, Rajavi stated: \"ISIS's conduct clearly benefits the Iranian regime's Supreme Leader Khamenei, who wholeheartedly welcomes it as an opportunity to overcome his regime's regional and international impasse and isolation. The founder and the number one [[Iran and state-sponsored terrorism|state sponsor of terror]] is thus trying to switch the place of murderer and the victim and portray the central banker of terrorism as a victim.\"<ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/just-because-isis-attacked-iran-doesnt-mean-iran-isnt-supporting-terrorism/article/2625674 Just because ISIS attacked Iran doesn't mean Iran isn't supporting terrorism]. 12 June 2017. Retrieved 13 June 2017</ref>\n\nA 10-point manifesto published by Maryam Rajavi sets out a programme to transform Iran. She states her commitment to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and to other international instruments. She calls for the abolition of the death penalty, the creation of a modern legal system and the independence of judges. Rajavi would end Tehran\u2019s funding of [[Hamas]], [[Hezbollah]] and other militant groups and is committed to peaceful coexistence, relations with all countries and respect for the United Nations charter.<ref>[http://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2016-12-08/debates/1117FCF0-EE8C-4A7A-BED2-DE9108AD65DC/IranHumanRights?highlight=Maryam%20Rajavi#contribution-6C120466-1CAA-4B8A-9EB6-E39D862B33EB Iran: Human Rights Debate in the UK House of Lords, House of Lord Hansard, 8 December 2016 ] [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This article contains quotations from this source, which is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/  Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref>  The manifesto also contains the statement that 'We recognize private property, private investment and the market economy.'<ref>https://www.usfliberty.org/maryam-rajavi/</ref>.\n\nRajavi presented her plan at the Council of Europe in 2006, which supports complete gender equality in political and social rights and, specifically, a commitment to equal participation of women in political leadership. Her 10-point plan for the future of Iran stipulates that any form of discrimination against women would be abolished and that women would enjoy the right to choose their clothing freely. It also includes the ending of cruel and degrading punishments.<ref>[http://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-06-28/debates/92B47430-75B2-40B5-9FA6-76A24E8D1E7C/HumanRightsInIran?highlight=Maryam%20Rajavi#contribution-85B1A801-C8A8-449C-8097-8267042F9C10 Human Rights in Iran, Debate in the UK House of Commons, House of Commons Hansard, 28 June 2016] [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This article contains quotations from this source, which is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/  Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref>\n\nOn October 2011 [[Theresa May]] banned Maryam Rajavi from coming to Britain in a trip where she was to \"explain how women are mistreated in Iran\". The high court then sued Theresa May, with Lord Carlile of Berriew (the Government's former independent reviewer of counter-terrorism laws) saying that May's decision \"could be viewed as appeasing the Mullahs\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/may-appeases-iran-with-ban-on-opposition-leader-bmdfx3w70fg |title=Iraqi court seeks arrest of Iranian exiles|access-date=21 January 2020|publisher=[[The Times]]|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/may-is-appeasing-iran-by-blocking-dissidents-visit-7445975.html |title=May 'is appeasing Iran' by blocking dissident's visit|access-date=21 January 2020|publisher=The Standard|}}</ref> In 2014, [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] dismissed an appeal from Lord Carlile of Berriew QC and others and upheld it to maintain the ban, which had originally being implemented in 1997. Members of the UK House of Lords argued that the Home Secretary was \"violating Article 10 (freedom of expression) of the European Convention of Human Rights (the Convention)\", saying that \"Home Secretary\u2019s reasons were legally irrelevant, because they depended on the potential reaction of a foreign state which did not share the values embodied in the Convention.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barakatt|first1=Marina|title=U.K. Supreme Court Upholds Home Secretary\u2019s Decision to Prevent an Iranian Politician from Entering the U.K. (November 12, 2014)|url=https://www.asil.org/blogs/uk-supreme-court-upholds-home-secretary%E2%80%99s-decision-prevent-iranian-politician-entering-uk|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=14 September 2016|publisher=The American Society of International Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=R (on the application of Lord Carlile of Berriew QC and others) (Appellants) v Secretary of State for the Home Department (Respondent) [2014] UKSC 60|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927010314/https://www.supremecourt.uk/decided-cases/docs/UKSC_2013_0098_PressSummary.pdf|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/decided-cases/docs/UKSC_2013_0098_PressSummary.pdf|archive-date=25 November 2017|accessdate=14 September 2016|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom}}</ref> Rajavi is not excluded from any other European country and engages regularly with parliamentarians in the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parliamentarians lose Maryam Rajavi court battle|url=http://www.hillingdontimes.co.uk/news/11596593.Parliamentarians_lose_Maryam_Rajavi_court_battle/?ref=mr|website=Hillingdon & Uxbridge Times|publisher=Hillingdon & Uxbridge Times|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Election (Constituency) !! Votes !! % !! Rank !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n|1980||[[1980 Iranian legislative election|Parliament]] {{small|([[Tehran, Rey, Shemiranat and Eslamshahr (electoral district)|Tehran, Rey and Shemiranat]])}}||221,831||10.4||67th\n| style=\"background-color:#C66\"|Lost\n|<ref>{{citation|date=5 April 1980|orig-year=16 Farvardin 1359|access-date=20 January 2020|title=\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0632\u062f\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0647 \u0628\u06cc\u0634 \u0627\u0632 \u06f1\u06f0 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0631\u0623\u06cc \u0622\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0647\u200c\u0627\u0646\u062f|url=https://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/detail/Manchester~18~18~906~226953:15m4471|newspaper=Kayhan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429044711/https://luna.manchester.ac.uk/luna/servlet/detail/Manchester~18~18~906~226953:15m4471|archive-date=29 April 2019|number=10964|page=3|language=Persian|trans-title=Names of Tehran candidates who gained more than 10,000 votes|via=The University of Manchester Library|id=15m4471|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Trials ==\n=== France ===\nOn 17 June 2003, Maryam Rajavi was arrested by [[Paris Police Prefecture]] alongside some 150 MEK members.<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/2996132.stm|title=Paris police target Iranian groups|date=17 June 2003|access-date=28 December 2016|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Rajavi released on bail|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=4 July 2003|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/07/200849135442456351.html}}</ref> Rajavi denied the charges, saying \"the case was mounted to appease Iran.\"<ref>{{citation|first= |last= |title=France drops charges against Iran opposition group |publisher=Fox News|date= |access-date=|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/france-drops-charges-against-iran-opposition-group}}</ref> All charges were later dropped.<ref name=\"reuters\"/><ref>{{citation|first=David|last=Jolly|title=France Will Drop Charges Against Iranian Dissidents |publisher=The New York Times|date=12 May 2011|access-date=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/world/europe/13iht-iran13.html}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters\">{{citation|title=France drops case against Iranian dissidents after 11-year probe |publisher=Reuters|date=17 September 2014|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-iran-ncri/france-drops-case-against-iranian-dissidents-after-11-year-probe-idUSKBN0HC1OR20140917}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=France Drops Case Against Iranian Dissidents|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=17 September 2014|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/france-drops-iran-dissidents-case/26590826.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq ===\nIn July 2010, the [[Supreme Iraqi Criminal Tribunal|Iraqi High Tribunal]] issued an [[arrest warrant]] for 39 MEK members, including Rajavi, \"due to evidence that confirms they committed [[crimes against humanity]]\" by \"involvement with the [[Iraqi Intelligence Service|former Iraqi security forces]] in suppressing the [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|1991 uprising]] against the former Iraqi regime and the killing of Iraqi citizens\". The MEK have denied the charges, saying that they constitute a \"politically motivated decision and it\u2019s the last gift presented from the government of Nuri al-Maliki to the Iranian government\".<ref name=\"cah\">{{cite web|author=Muhanad Mohammed|editor=Rania El Gamal; David Stamp|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE66A0A0|title=Iraqi court seeks arrest of Iranian exiles|date=11 July 2010|access-date=28 December 2016|publisher=[[Reuters]]|quote=Rajavi\u2019s wife Maryam, leader of the French-based National Council of Resistance of Iran (NCRI), the PMOI\u2019s political wing, was also included in the warrant, Abdul Sahib added.}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Iran|Biography}}\n*[[List of Iranian women]]\n*[[List of people from Tehran]] \n*[[France\u2013Iran relations]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.maryam-rajavi.com/en/ }}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Massoud Rajavi]]|as=Leader of People's Mujahedin of Iran}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Co-leader of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]|years=1985\u2013present|alongside=[[Massoud Rajavi]]}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Abolhassan Banisadr]]|as=President of Iran in pretence}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President-elect of the [[National Council of Resistance of Iran]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Massoud Rajavi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretay-General of [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]]|years=1989\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=Fahimeh Arvani}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the [[People's Mujahedin of Iran]] military wing|years=1987\u20131993}}\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajavi, Maryam}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sharif University of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Mujahedin of Iran politicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian women in politics]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by Iraq]]\n[[Category:National Council of Resistance of Iran members]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on crimes against humanity charges]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:NCRI\u2192National Council of Resistance of Iran", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryam_Rajavi"}
{"title_page": "Tony Clarke (British politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Tony Clarke}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Tony Clarke\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        = Tony Clarke at Milton Malsor.jpg\n|imagesize    =\n|alt          =\n|caption      = Clarke, second left, with his then constituency residents in [[Milton Malsor]] village hall at the launch of their Parish Plan, January 2003\n|constituency_MP = [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]]\n|parliament   =\n|majority     =\n|term_start   = 1 May 1997\n|term_end     = 11 April 2005\n|predecessor  = [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]]\n|successor    = [[Brian Binley]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1963|09|6|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Northampton]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|restingplace =\n|birthname    =\n|nationality  = British\n|party        = [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]]\n|otherparty   = Independent (2007-2013) <br /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (until 2007)\n|spouse       =\n|relations    =\n|children     =\n|residence    = Northampton\n|alma_mater   =\n|occupation   = Northampton Borough Councillor 2007 - 5 May 2011\n|profession   =\n|cabinet      =\n|committees   =\n|portfolio    =\n|religion     =\n|signature    =\n|signature_alt=\n|website      =\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Anthony Richard Clarke''' (born 6 September 1963, [[Northampton]], England), known as '''Tony Clarke''' is a former Member of Parliament and ex General Manager of Northampton Town Football Club. He is currently a teacher at Northampton College. A politician of the left, Clarke was until  was until recently the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] National Spokesperson on International and Foreign Affairs; previously a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, he was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]] from 1997\u20132005. Clarke was also a director of Northampton Town Football Club for 11 years 1999- 2010 and as General Manager at the club between 2005 and 2008. He served three terms (12 years) on Northampton Borough Council (2 Labour, 1 Independent) and one term (4 years) on Northamptonshire County Council (Independent) He also served as a Special Constable with Northamptonshire Police between 2003 and 2007.\n\nOn 11 March 2013, Clarke announced that he had joined the Green Party, and would campaign as an Independent Green and stand as a Green Party candidate in the [[2013 Northamptonshire County Council election|2013 local elections]]. He is quoted as saying: \"I left the Labour Party, and then discovered that really it had left me, I have battled on as an Independent to try to make a difference for local people and have had some successes, but now it is time to truly give the power back to the people. I have chosen to campaign and as an Independent Green and proudly display the Green Party Logo on the ballot paper\".<ref name = \"NC&E_14_03_2013\">[http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/ex-northampton-south-mp-tony-clarke-joins-the-green-party-1-4885070 ''Ex-Northampton South MP Tony Clarke joins the Green Party'' Northampton Chronicle & Echo 14 March 2013, accessed 14 March 2013\"]</ref>  Tony Clarke is still a local community activist in Northampton and is currently employed teaching public Services at Northampton College.\n\n==Labour Councillor and former MP==\nBefore becoming an MP, Clarke had previously been a Social Work lecturer and Labour Councillor on [[Northampton Borough Council]]. He won the parliamentary seat unexpectedly at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] with a majority of 744 <ref>{{cite web|title = General Election results|url = http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/constit/191.htm|accessdate = 2008-06-06}}</ref> over the sitting [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]], with a campaign based on local representation. Morris, the [[Deputy Speaker of the House of Commons]], had a 14,000 vote majority at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], and the seat was considered safe for the Conservatives.\n\nAt the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], Clarke held the seat with a majority of 885 votes over the Conservative candidate [[Shailesh Vara]]. However, Conservative [[Brian Binley]] took the seat with a majority of 4,419 at the May 2005 General Election.\n\nClarke was regarded as a rebel and an anti-war MP.  Despite his stance against the invasion of Iraq, on receiving a copy of a confidential memo between [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] [[Tony Blair]], and [[US President]] [[George W. Bush]], he chose to report the leak to the police (to protect those in the theatre of war) rather than publicly expose what was said.<ref name=\"Pair are guilty of Bush memo leak\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/6637735.stm Pair are guilty of Bush memo leak]</ref><ref name= \"Pair are sentenced\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/6641983.stm Pair given custodial sentences]</ref> From 2003 to 2005 he chaired the Northern Ireland Select Committee (Delegated Affairs) during the suspension of the NI Assembly.\n\n==Labour expulsion and independent councillor==\nIn May 2007, he was chosen by Northampton Labour Party to stand in the safe Labour Castle ward for the 3 May local elections. The decision created a split between the local Labour Party and the Labour party nationally and regionally, and the reasons have never been clear. It is speculated that the regional and national party forced Clarke out and selected their own candidate Tess Scott on an all women short list against the local party's wishes and outside of the Labour Party rules. They then selected Clarke and had three candidates for a two-member ward before telling him he could not stand.  As a result, Clarke decided to stand as an Independent and fight against the official Labour Party candidate in Castle ward, a decision which resulted in his expulsion from the Labour Party. Castle was a two-member ward but unusually Labour could only field one candidate.\n\nEight other local Labour members were also expelled; including Clarke's running mate in the election, Peter Evans, also a previous Borough Councillor; John Dickie, a former Labour leader of the Borough Council; and a second former Labour leader of the Borough Council, Geoff Howes. Howes had also been a Mayor of the town who, not long before, had been elected by the then controlling Labour party as a [[Freedom of the City|Freeman of the Borough]]. Clarke said: \"...They [Labour] have shot themselves in the foot. This...was a contributing factor to their losses...[in the May 2007 borough elections]\".<ref name =\"NCE2007_05_08\">{{cite web|title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Labour ousts the political heavyweights |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news?articleid=2859745|accessdate = 28 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nClark won the Castle seat on [[Northampton Borough Council]].<ref>{{cite web|title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Election Shock|url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Election-shock.2227381.jp\n|accessdate = 2008-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Northampton Borough Council Election Results 2007|url = http://www.northampton.gov.uk/downloads/declaration_of_results.pdf|accessdate = 22 February 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Out of 47 councillors on the borough council, Labour ended up with only 5 seats, the Conservatives 15, and Clarke as the sole independent. The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] took control with 26 seats, the first time for about 80 years since the Liberals were last in control. Clarke lost his seat at the May 2011 election to Labour, though the Conservatives regained control of the council.\n\n==Re-instatement==\nIn December 2008, Howes expulsion was reversed and he was reinstated two days before his appeal was due to be heard by the Labour Party's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC). He was selected as the Labour candidate for a Northampton Borough Council by-election to be held 22 January 2009.<ref name=\"2009ByElection\">{{cite web|title=Northampton Borough Council'' - Statement of Persons Nominated |url=http://www.northampton.gov.uk/downloads/Persons_Nominated.doc |accessdate=31 December 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n</ref> However, no official announcement was made by the local party on the status of Clarke or the other two candidates, Evans and Dickie, previously expelled. Dickie was Clarke's [[election agent]] at the 2010 General Election where Clarke came fourth with 5.8% of the vote, being one of only a small handful of Independents nationally to save their [[Deposit (politics)|deposit]].<ref>John Dickie column in the Northampton Chronicle & Echo, 12 May 2010, p11</ref>\n\n==2009 Northampton Borough Council by-election ==\nIn January 2009, Howes stood as a Labour candidate in a Borough Council by-election finishing a distant second to the Conservatives. Howes' selection was without the prior knowledge of the group's leader on the Council. A row subsequently erupted when Clarke appeared in Labour by-election literature, endorsing the party's candidate. This resulted in Howes and election Agent Anjona Roy also being expelled<ref name=\"2009ByElection2\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Investigation over Northampton by-election leaflet - Northampton Chronicle & Echo\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Investigation-over-Northampton-byelection-leaflet.5030305.jpg\n |accessdate = 4 March 2009\n }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\nHowes died in December 2014 aged 67.<ref name = \"Howesdeath\">\n {{cite web\n |title = 'Fat' Northampton political figure Geoff Howes dies aged 67\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/towering-northampton-political-figure-geoff-howes-dies-aged-67-1-6472186  \n| newspaper=Northampton Chronicle & Echo \n |date = 12 December 2014\n |accessdate= 26 April 2014}}\n</ref>\n\n==2009 & 2013 Northants County Council elections==\nThe voters in Castle ward in the centre of Northampton picked Clarke to represent them on the county council at 4 June 2009 County Council elections. Clarke now represented the Castle ward as an independent on both Northampton borough and  Northamptonshire county councils. He said: \"The people have spoken and I'll now take this all the way to the General Election to give the people the chance to vote independent\". At the count he was observed to have been congratulated by his old Labour colleagues Dickie and Howes (see above).<ref name =\"2009NCC1\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Tony Clark triumphs as independent - Northampton Chronicle and Echo 6 June 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Tony-Clarke-triumphs-as-independent.5341307.jp |accessdate = 7 June 2009 }}\n</ref> He beat the official Labour candidate into second place in what is normally a solid Labour county council division.<ref name =\"2009NCC2\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Northants Council Council official election results 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonshire.gov.uk/election2009/DivisionResults.aspx?id=37 |accessdate = 7 June 2009 }}\n</ref> In September 2009, the national Labour Party suspended Northampton South Constituency Labour Party. The local paper reported that the move was made after Clarke was featured in local Labour literature given out during the January by-election.<ref name = \"C&E20090911\">{{cite web\n |title = Labour Party suspends political group - Northampton Chronicle and Echo 11 September 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Labour-Party-suspends-political-group.5638628.jp |accessdate =11 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Northamptonshire County Council election]], Clarke stood as a candidate for Castle Division coming second with 437 votes to the winning Labour candidate's 806.\n\n==2010 General Election==\nIn August 2008, Clarke stated that he would stand against Labour as an independent at the next Parliamentary Election for Northampton South Constituency and did so on 6 May 2010. He polled fourth with 2,242 votes, behind the three main parties' candidates, and avoiding losing his deposit. His campaign cost over \u00a38,000.<ref>{{cite web\n |title = Northampton Chronicle & Echo 'Revealed: The \u00a340,000 cost of fighting the election'\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Revealed-The-40000-cost-of.6415221.jp\n }}</ref>  He lost his borough seat to Labour in 2011.<ref>\n  {{Cite news\n  | last = Bontoft\n  | first = Wayne\n  | author-link =\n  | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = Labour's search for candidate launched\n  | newspaper = Northampton Chronicle & Echo\n  | pages = 2\n  | date = 5 August 2008\n  | url =\n  | postscript = <!--None--> }}\n</ref>\nThe boundary of the constituency changed for the 2010 election with the loss of some parts of the southern and western areas to the Daventry and the new South Northamptonshire constituency. The areas lost were generally be considered Conservative, thus increasing the possibility of Labour regaining the seat. However, it remained firmly Conservative with Clarke's intervention, having an effect on the Labour vote. Clarke had earlier said: ''\"...I think the only chance they [Labour] had of winning went out of the window when they declared internal war on half the membership [of the local Labour party] in 2005. It should be a safe Labour seat, but I'll stand as an independent and I'll take on Brian Binley if they can't.\"''\n\nLabour's choice of official candidate was announced in November 2008 as Clyde Loakes, who was born and brought up in Northamptonshire, and who went on to become leader of [[Waltham Forest]] council in north-east London.<ref name =\"NCE2008_11_04\">\n {{cite web\n |title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Council leader is Labour candidate\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Council-leader-is-Labour-candidate.4656116.jp\n |accessdate = 4 November 2008 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name =\"WFG\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Waltham Forest Guardian\n |url = http://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/wfnews/3759505.WALTHAM_FOREST__Leader_shortlisted_for_Northamp%20ton_seat/#show |accessdate = 29 December 2008 }}\n</ref>\nLoakes was absent for much of the campaign.\nNorthampton Borough Council member for [[West Hunsbury]] 2007\u20132011, Paul Varnsverry was selected in October 2008 as the Liberal Democrat's prospective parliamentary candidate for Northampton South which was won by the Conservatives.<ref name =\"NCE2008_10_02\">\n {{cite web\n |title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Lib Dems choose their man\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Lib-Dems-choose-their-man.4549497.jp\n |accessdate = 4 November 2008}}\n</ref>\n\n==2015 General Election==\nClarke stood for election again in Northampton, this time changing his constituency to [[Northampton North]] and as a [[The Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] candidate. He achieved 1,503 votes (3.8%) beating the  [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate Angela Patterson (3.6%). The seat was held by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Michael Ellis (British politician)]] who received 16,699 votes (42.4%). His old [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] colleague [[Sally Keeble]] achieved second place with a 34.1% share of the votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Northampton North parliamentary constituency 2015 BBC Election Result|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000861|website=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Coorparation|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe wrongly claimed that a company backed by City financier [[Nathaniel Philip Rothschild]] had been funding terrorists.<ref>http://www.cityam.com/228973/green-party-left-red-faced-after-accusing-oil-firm-of-buying-from-isis</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080514172747/http://www.nnclp.org/ Northampton North Labour Party]\n*[http://www.labour2win.org Northampton South CLP Labour2win.org]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.northampton.gov.uk/site/index.php Northampton Borough Council]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n  | before = [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]]\n  | after  = [[Brian Binley]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Tony}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of Northamptonshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Independent British political candidates]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:British special constables]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Tony Clarke}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Tony Clarke\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        = Tony Clarke at Milton Malsor.jpg\n|imagesize    =\n|alt          =\n|caption      = Clarke, second left, with his then constituency residents in [[Milton Malsor]] village hall at the launch of their Parish Plan, January 2003\n|constituency_MP = [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]]\n|parliament   =\n|majority     =\n|term_start   = 1 May 1997\n|term_end     = 11 April 2005\n|predecessor  = [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]]\n|successor    = [[Brian Binley]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1963|09|6|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Northampton]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|restingplace =\n|birthname    =\n|nationality  = British\n|party        = [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]]\n|otherparty   = Independent (2007-2013) <br /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (until 2007)\n|spouse       =\n|relations    =\n|children     =\n|residence    = Northampton\n|alma_mater   =\n|occupation   = Northampton Borough Councillor 2007 - 5 May 2011\n|profession   =\n|cabinet      =\n|committees   =\n|portfolio    =\n|religion     =\n|signature    =\n|signature_alt=\n|website      =\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Anthony Richard Clarke''' (born 6 September 1963, [[Northampton]], England), known as '''Tony Clarke''' is a former Member of Parliament and ex General Manager of Northampton Town Football Club. He is currently a teacher at Northampton College. A politician of the left, Clarke was until  was until recently the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] National Spokesperson on International and Foreign Affairs; previously a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, he was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]] from 1997-2005. Clarke was also a director of Northampton Town Football Club for 11 years 1999- 2010 and as General Manager at the club between 2005 and 2008. He served three terms (12 years) on Northampton Borough Council (2 Labour, 1 Independent) and one term (4 years) on Northamptonshire County Council (Independent) He also served as a Special Constable with Northamptonshire Police between 2003 and 2007.\n\nOn 11 March 2013, Clarke announced that he had joined the Green Party, and would campaign as an Independent Green and stand as a Green Party candidate in the [[2013 Northamptonshire County Council election|2013 local elections]]. He is quoted as saying: \"I left the Labour Party, and then discovered that really it had left me, I have battled on as an Independent to try to make a difference for local people and have had some successes, but now it is time to truly give the power back to the people. I have chosen to campaign and as an Independent Green and proudly display the Green Party Logo on the ballot paper\".<ref name = \"NC&E_14_03_2013\">[http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/ex-northampton-south-mp-tony-clarke-joins-the-green-party-1-4885070 ''Ex-Northampton South MP Tony Clarke joins the Green Party'' Northampton Chronicle & Echo 14 March 2013, accessed 14 March 2013\"]</ref>  Tony Clarke is still a local community activist in Northampton and is currently employed teaching public Services at Northampton College.\n\n==Labour Councillor and former MP==\nBefore becoming an MP, Clarke had previously been a Social Work lecturer and Labour Councillor on [[Northampton Borough Council]]. He won the parliamentary seat unexpectedly at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] with a majority of 744 <ref>{{cite web|title = General Election results|url = http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/constit/191.htm|accessdate = 2008-06-06}}</ref> over the sitting [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]], with a campaign based on local representation. Morris, the [[Deputy Speaker of the House of Commons]], had a 14,000 vote majority at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], and the seat was considered safe for the Conservatives.\n\nAt the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], Clarke held the seat with a majority of 885 votes over the Conservative candidate [[Shailesh Vara]]. However, Conservative [[Brian Binley]] took the seat with a majority of 4,419 at the May 2005 General Election.\n\nClarke was regarded as a rebel and an anti-war MP.  Despite his stance against the invasion of Iraq, on receiving a copy of a confidential memo between [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] [[Tony Blair]], and [[US President]] [[George W. Bush]], he chose to report the leak to the police (to protect those in the theatre of war) rather than publicly expose what was said.<ref name=\"Pair are guilty of Bush memo leak\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/6637735.stm Pair are guilty of Bush memo leak]</ref><ref name= \"Pair are sentenced\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/6641983.stm Pair given custodial sentences]</ref> From 2003 to 2005 he chaired the Northern Ireland Select Committee (Delegated Affairs) during the suspension of the NI Assembly.\n\n==Labour expulsion and independent councillor==\nIn May 2007, he was chosen by Northampton Labour Party to stand in the safe Labour Castle ward for the 3 May local elections. The decision created a split between the local Labour Party and the Labour party nationally and regionally, and the reasons have never been clear. It is speculated that the regional and national party forced Clarke out and selected their own candidate Tess Scott on an all women short list against the local party's wishes and outside of the Labour Party rules. They then selected Clarke and had three candidates for a two member ward before telling him he could not stand.  As a result, Clarke decided to stand as an Independent and fight against the official Labour Party candidate in Castle ward, a decision which resulted in his expulsion from the Labour Party. Castle was a two-member ward but unusually Labour could only field one candidate.\n\nEight other local Labour members were also expelled; including Clarke's running mate in the election, Peter Evans, also a previous Borough Councillor; John Dickie, a former Labour leader of the Borough Council; and a second former Labour leader of the Borough Council, Geoff Howes. Howes had also been a Mayor of the town who, not long before, had been elected by the then controlling Labour party as a [[Freedom of the City|Freeman of the Borough]]. Clarke said: \"...They [Labour] have shot themselves in the foot. This...was a contributing factor to their losses...[in the May 2007 borough elections]\".<ref name =\"NCE2007_05_08\">{{cite web|title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Labour ousts the political heavyweights |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news?articleid=2859745|accessdate = 28 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nClark won the Castle seat on [[Northampton Borough Council]].<ref>{{cite web|title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Election Shock|url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Election-shock.2227381.jp\n|accessdate = 2008-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Northampton Borough Council Election Results 2007|url = http://www.northampton.gov.uk/downloads/declaration_of_results.pdf|accessdate = 22 February 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Out of 47 councillors on the borough council, Labour ended up with only 5 seats, the Conservatives 15, and Clarke as the sole independent. The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] took control with 26 seats, the first time for about 80 years since the Liberals were last in control. Clarke lost his seat at the May 2011 election to Labour, though the Conservatives regained control of the council.\n\n==Re-instatement==\nIn December 2008, Howes expulsion was reversed and he was reinstated two days before his appeal was due to be heard by the Labour Party's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC). He was selected as the Labour candidate for a Northampton Borough Council by-election to be held 22 January 2009.<ref name=\"2009ByElection\">{{cite web|title=Northampton Borough Council'' - Statement of Persons Nominated |url=http://www.northampton.gov.uk/downloads/Persons_Nominated.doc |accessdate=31 December 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n</ref> However, no official announcement was made by the local party on the status of Clarke or the other two candidates, Evans and Dickie, previously expelled. Dickie was Clarke's [[election agent]] at the 2010 General Election where Clarke came fourth with 5.8% of the vote, being one of only a small handful of Independents nationally to save their [[Deposit (politics)|deposit]].<ref>John Dickie column in the Northampton Chronicle & Echo, 12 May 2010, p11</ref>\n\n==2009 Northampton Borough Council by-election ==\nIn January 2009, Howes stood as a Labour candidate in a Borough Council by-election finishing a distant second to the Conservatives. Howes' selection was without the prior knowledge of the group's leader on the Council. A row subsequently erupted when Clarke appeared in Labour by-election literature, endorsing the party's candidate. This resulted in Howes and election Agent Anjona Roy also being expelled<ref name=\"2009ByElection2\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Investigation over Northampton by-election leaflet - Northampton Chronicle & Echo\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Investigation-over-Northampton-byelection-leaflet.5030305.jpg\n |accessdate = 4 March 2009\n }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\nHowes died in December 2014 aged 67.<ref name = \"Howesdeath\">\n {{cite web\n |title = 'Fat' Northampton political figure Geoff Howes dies aged 67\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/towering-northampton-political-figure-geoff-howes-dies-aged-67-1-6472186  \n| newspaper=Northampton Chronicle & Echo \n |date = 12 December 2014\n |accessdate= 26 April 2014}}\n</ref>\n\n==2009 & 2013 Northants County Council elections==\nThe voters in Castle ward in the centre of Northampton picked Clarke to represent them on the county council at 4 June 2009 County Council elections. Clarke now represented the Castle ward as an independent on both Northampton borough and  Northamptonshire county councils. He said: \"The people have spoken and I'll now take this all the way to the General Election to give the people the chance to vote independent\". At the count he was observed to have been congratulated by his old Labour colleagues Dickie and Howes (see above).<ref name =\"2009NCC1\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Tony Clark triumphs as independent - Northampton Chronicle and Echo 6 June 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Tony-Clarke-triumphs-as-independent.5341307.jp |accessdate = 7 June 2009 }}\n</ref> He beat the official Labour candidate into second place in what is normally a solid Labour county council division.<ref name =\"2009NCC2\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Northants Council Council official election results 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonshire.gov.uk/election2009/DivisionResults.aspx?id=37 |accessdate = 7 June 2009 }}\n</ref> In September 2009, the national Labour Party suspended Northampton South Constituency Labour Party. The local paper reported that the move was made after Clarke was featured in local Labour literature given out during the January by-election.<ref name = \"C&E20090911\">{{cite web\n |title = Labour Party suspends political group - Northampton Chronicle and Echo 11 September 2009\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Labour-Party-suspends-political-group.5638628.jp |accessdate =11 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Northamptonshire County Council election]], Clarke stood as a candidate for Castle Division coming second with 437 votes to the winning Labour candidate's 806.\n\n==2010 General Election==\nIn August 2008, Clarke stated that he would stand against Labour as an independent at the next Parliamentary Election for Northampton South Constituency and did so on 6 May 2010. He polled fourth with 2,242 votes, behind the three main parties' candidates, and avoiding losing his deposit. His campaign cost over \u00a38,000.<ref>{{cite web\n |title = Northampton Chronicle & Echo 'Revealed: The \u00a340,000 cost of fighting the election'\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Revealed-The-40000-cost-of.6415221.jp\n }}</ref>  He lost his borough seat to Labour in 2011.<ref>\n  {{Cite news\n  | last = Bontoft\n  | first = Wayne\n  | author-link =\n  | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = Labour's search for candidate launched\n  | newspaper = Northampton Chronicle & Echo\n  | pages = 2\n  | date = 5 August 2008\n  | url =\n  | postscript = <!--None--> }}\n</ref>\nThe boundary of the constituency changed for the 2010 election with the loss of some parts of the southern and western areas to the Daventry and the new South Northamptonshire constituency. The areas lost were generally be considered Conservative, thus increasing the possibility of Labour regaining the seat. However, it remained firmly Conservative with Clarke's intervention, having an effect on the Labour vote. Clarke had earlier said: ''\"...I think the only chance they [Labour] had of winning went out of the window when they declared internal war on half the membership [of the local Labour party] in 2005. It should be a safe Labour seat, but I'll stand as an independent and I'll take on Brian Binley if they can't.\"''\n\nLabour's choice of official candidate was announced in November 2008 as Clyde Loakes, who was born and brought up in Northamptonshire, and who went on to become leader of [[Waltham Forest]] council in north-east London.<ref name =\"NCE2008_11_04\">\n {{cite web\n |title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Council leader is Labour candidate\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Council-leader-is-Labour-candidate.4656116.jp\n |accessdate = 4 November 2008 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name =\"WFG\">\n {{cite web\n |title = Waltham Forest Guardian\n |url = http://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/wfnews/3759505.WALTHAM_FOREST__Leader_shortlisted_for_Northamp%20ton_seat/#show |accessdate = 29 December 2008 }}\n</ref>\nLoakes was absent for much of the campaign.\nNorthampton Borough Council member for [[West Hunsbury]] 2007-2011, Paul Varnsverry was selected in October 2008 as the Liberal Democrat's prospective parliamentary candidate for Northampton South which was won by the Conservatives.<ref name =\"NCE2008_10_02\">\n {{cite web\n |title = ''Northampton Chronicle & Echo'' Lib Dems choose their man\n |url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/Lib-Dems-choose-their-man.4549497.jp\n |accessdate = 4 November 2008}}\n</ref>\n\n==2015 General Election==\nClarke stood for election again in Northampton, this time changing his constituency to [[Northampton North]] and as a [[The Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] candidate. He achieved 1,503 votes (3.8%) beating the  [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate Angela Patterson (3.6%). The seat was held by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Michael Ellis (British politician)]] who received 16,699 votes (42.4%). His old [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] colleague [[Sally Keeble]] achieved second place with a 34.1% share of the votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Northampton North parliamentary constituency 2015 BBC Election Result|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000861|website=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Coorparation|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe wrongly claimed that a company backed by City financier [[Nathaniel Philip Rothschild]] had been funding terrorists.<ref>http://www.cityam.com/228973/green-party-left-red-faced-after-accusing-oil-firm-of-buying-from-isis</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080514172747/http://www.nnclp.org/ Northampton North Labour Party]\n*[http://www.labour2win.org Northampton South CLP Labour2win.org]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.northampton.gov.uk/site/index.php Northampton Borough Council]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Northampton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton South]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n  | before = [[Michael Morris, Baron Naseby|Michael Morris]]\n  | after  = [[Brian Binley]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Tony}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of Northamptonshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Independent British political candidates]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:British special constables]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: two member \u2192 two-member, 1997-2005 \u2192 1997\u20132005 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Clarke_(British_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Alec Benjamin", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Alec Benjamin\n| image            = Alec Benjamin.png\n| caption          = Benjamin in 2019\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1994|05|28}}\n| birth_place      = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], U.S.\n| background       = solo_singer\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| genre            = [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/alec-benjamin-mn0003523439/biography|title=Alec Benjamin Biography & History|website=[[AllMusic]]|last=Donelson|first=Marcy|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[Warner/Chappell Music]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| years_active     = 2013&ndash;present\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Jon Bellion]]|[[Matisyahu]]|[[Dan Wilson (musician)|Dan Wilson]]|[[Sacha Skarbek]]|[[Jamie Scott]]||[[Julie Frost]]||[[John Mayer]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.alecbenjamin.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Alec Shane Benjamin''' (born May 28, 1994)<ref name=\"get to know\" /> is an American singer and songwriter from [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=\"get to know\">{{cite web|title=Get-To-Know Alec Benjamin and his excellent debut single \"Paper Crown\" |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/news-story-get-to-know-alec-benjamin-my-musical-mind.html}}</ref> He has gained popularity from his [[Pop music|pop]] songs that depict descriptive stories from his own personal experiences. He also gained much attention from his demos.  In addition, to his solo project, Benjamin has found success in songwriting with artists such as [[Jon Bellion]], including a songwriting credit on the track \"New York Soul (Part II)\" from Bellion's album ''[[The Human Condition (Jon Bellion album)|The Human Condition]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Jon-bellion-new-york-soul-part-ii-lyrics|title=Jon Bellion - New York Soul (Part II)}}</ref> He is heavily influenced by artists such as [[Eminem]], [[John Mayer]], [[Paul Simon]] and [[Ben Gibbard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/alec-benjamin-paper-crown-music-video-exclusive-premiere|title=Press Play on This Exclusive \"Paper Crown\" Music Video, Fall Totally in Love with Jersey-Wearing, Boombox-Toting Alec Benjamin|last=Firman|first=Tehrene|website=Teen Vogue|access-date=2016-06-14}}</ref> In 2019, he recorded two singles with Spotify Studios NYC, one of them being a cover of Eminem's song, \"Stan.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/singer-songwriter-alec-benjamin-covers-eminem-s-stan-for-spotify|title=Singer-Songwriter Alec Benjamin Covers Eminem\u2019s \u201cStan\u201d For Spotify|website=Genius|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Alec Benjamin signed to Columbia Records, whilst still being enrolled at USC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.warnerchappell.com/artist-details/76|title=Alec Benjamin|website=Warnerchappel|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> However, Columbia Records then ended their partnership, before he was able to submit his album.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.royaloakmusictheatre.com/events/detail/390734|title=Alec Benjamin {{!}} Royal Oak Music Theatre|last=Theatre|first=Royal Oak Music|website=www.royaloakmusictheatre.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Despite this, he used other methods to gain a following: he performed his songs in parking lots outside [[Shawn Mendes]] and [[Troye Sivan]] concerts and handed out business cards to promote his work.<ref name=\":0\" /> He is considered to be a self-made artist; someone who had started from nowhere.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.warnermusic.com.au/news/get-to-know-alec-benjamin|title=WHO IS ALEC BENJAMIN?|website=www.warnermusic.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> . \n\nBenjamin's mixtape ''Narrated For You'' reached number 127 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in 2019. The mixtape features the songs \"The Water Fountain,\" and  \u201c[[Let Me Down Slowly]]\u201d, which was released as a single with [[Alessia Cara]]. In the first week, when his song ''Let Me Down Slowly'' came out, it gained over 2 million streams and has over 540 million streams as of March 2020.<ref name=\":1\" />  He made his US television debut when he performed his US platinum single, \"Let Me Down Slowly\" on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' on January 8, 2019. In his mixtape he tells stories of love, friendship, and growing up.\n\nBenjamin's song \"I Built a Friend\" was used as backing material for a contemporary dance audition of contestant Merrick Hanna, on episode 1 of the [[America's Got Talent (season 12)|12th season]] of ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' (May 30, 2017). Benjamin has created \"Can I Sing For You?\" videos on YouTube in which he performs his written songs in acoustic to people in public.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Title\n! Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''These Two Windows''\n|\n* Scheduled: May 29, 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/these-two-windows/1498270787 |title=These Two Windows \u2013 Album by Alec Benjamin on Apple Music |website=Apple Music US |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* Label: Atlantic\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n|}\n\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/alec-benjamin/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Alec Benjamin Chart History: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/alec-benjamin/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Alec Benjamin Chart History: Canadian Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Hitlisten|DEN]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=7&y=2019&list=a40|title=Album Top-40 Uge 7, 2019|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-album-megafusion/?ye=2019&we=28|title=Le Top de la semaine : Top Albums Fusionnes \u2013 SNEP (Week 28, 2019)|publisher=Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|language=French|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Album Top 100|NLD]]<br /><ref name=\"NLD\">{{Cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Alec+Benjamin&titel=Narrated+For+You&cat=a|title=Alec Benjamin - Narrated For You - dutchcharts.nl|website=dutchcharts.nl|language=Dutch|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[VG-lista|NOR]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vglista.no/topplister/topp-40-album-2019-04/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 40 Album uke 4, 2019|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/54?dspy=2019&dspp=14|title=Veckolista Album, vecka 14|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''America''<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n|\n* Released: April 22, 2013\n* Label: White Rope\n* Format: Digital download